<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1323,284,630]" box="[264,577,284,309]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis box="[264,577,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<typeStatus box="[264,319,284,309]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Type</typeStatus>
material of synonyms
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1323,284,630]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The 
<typeStatus box="[364,414,324,350]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[453,582,324,349]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="speciosa">
<emphasis box="[453,582,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">V. speciosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could not be found in any major Italian Museum (see acknowledgments) and is considered lost. This species is most likely a synonym of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lucas" authorityYear="1845" box="[1156,1322,364,389]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeangerardi">
<emphasis box="[1156,1322,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">V. jeangerardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on Costa’s description, and the fact that it is a common Mediterranean species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[264,1323,284,630]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The 
<typeStatus box="[366,416,444,470]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Claus" authorityYear="1872" box="[458,646,444,469]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mediterranea">
<emphasis box="[458,646,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">V. mediterranea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could not be found in any major European museum (see acknowledgments) and is considered lost. Claus merely lists this species as occurring in salps; there is no description or figures. Thus, it is a nomen nudum. It seems a synonym of 
<emphasis box="[295,468,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lucas" authorityYear="1845" box="[295,464,564,589]" class="Malacostraca" family="Vibiliidae" genus="Vibilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jeangerardi">V. jeangerardi</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
based solely on geographical grounds, and has been regarded as such, by subsequent authors. It has not been recognised as a valid species since 
<bibRefCitation author="Claus, C." box="[1100,1256,604,630]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref36413" refString="Claus, C. (1880) Grundzuge der Zoologie. Marburg." type="book" year="1880">Claus (1880)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
